  "prompt": "Can a Roman Catholic boy from Kerala marry a Hindu girl from another state?",
  "response": "In India, interfaith marriages are possible under the Special Marriage Act, which allows people from different religions to marry legally. However, such marriages can face social and family challenges. In this specific case:\n\n1. Legal Perspective:\n- The couple can marry under the Special Marriage Act\n- Both parties must be of marriageable age (males 21, females 18)\n- They need to give notice of marriage and follow legal procedures\n\n2. Social Considerations:\n- Families might oppose the interfaith marriage\n- There could be cultural and religious differences\n- Social acceptance may vary depending on individual families and communities\n\n3. Religious Perspective:\n- The Catholic Church traditionally discourages interfaith marriages\n- A Catholic partner might need to get special permission from the church\n- The Hindu partner may face potential family or community pressure\n\n4. Practical Steps:\n- Open communication with both families\n- Mutual respect for each other's religious beliefs\n- Potential premarital counseling\n- Understanding and navigating cultural differences\n\nWhile legally possible, such marriages require understanding, communication, and mutual respect from both partners and their families.",
